data.content:
**What happened:** C# 14 introduces new span conversions. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is not representable in a LINQ expression tree, it throws at runtime.

**Fix — pick one:**

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to resolve back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree compatible. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version).
